{
  "_about": "Golden-vector capture template for PanchangKit tests. PRIMARY locations are in the USA — this app's real users. India rows are kept only as cross-checks (so the engine also matches an India-computed panchang for family/travel). Fill each 'expected' block from the source in a browser, then drop this file at Tests/PanchangKitTests/Fixtures/golden_vectors.json. Do NOT compute expected values yourself — they must come from the source so the test stays independent of the engine.",
  "source": "drikpanchang.com (Drik Ganita method, Lahiri ayanamsa) — single consistent authority",
  "time_format": "24h, local time of the case's location. Suffix '+1' = time after midnight (next day). 'sunrise+1' = until next sunrise.",
  "_capture_instructions": [
    "1. On drikpanchang.com, switch the clock to 24-hour (or append ?time-format=24hour) so you transcribe HH:MM, not AM/PM. US pages default to AM/PM.",
    "2. Capture is grouped by location. For each block, set the site location ONCE via the search box to the named US/India city, then open each date URL in that block.",
    "3. Date URLs use ?date=DD/MM/YYYY and work in a real browser (only the automated fetcher dropped them, which is why this is a manual step).",
    "4. The Amanta/Purnimanta and Samvat rules are LOCATION-INDEPENDENT labeling — they're tested at US locations here. For the two rows sharing a date+location with different 'preset', toggle the site's Amanta/Purnimanta switch between captures; only the month label should change.",
    "5. End times: write the clock time; append '+1' if after midnight.",
    "6. Spot-check a few (month labels, festivals) against the printed panchang your family trusts before treating this as ground truth.",
    "7. Engine tolerances (SPEC §9): tithi/nakshatra/yoga ends within ~1-2 min; sunrise/sunset within ~1 min. Small diffs from the source are expected."
  ],
